@NODE Funktion "Function of the program"

InSpace insert a user-defined number of spaces (ins-space->inspace)
at every beginning of a standart ASCII text file. This is, e.g., re-
quired for each text of the German 'electronic' amiga magazine NoCover
(club-magazine of the German amiga club 'APC&TCP'). If you have for-
gotten to use these spaces or if you find it to complicated to think
of them when writing your text you could use InSpace: @{"Usage" LINK Benutzung}

And to all of you who still wonder wether InSpace will run on your
system: @{"Requirements" LINK Voraussetzungen}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Voraussetzungen "Requirements"

The program requires at least Workbench/Kickstart 2.04 and @{"MUI" LINK Readme.mui/Main}
(I think at least version 2.x, but perhaps everyone could have got the
actual version 3.3 which is to be found on a lot of CD-ROMs and on the
Aminet).

If someone requests a version without MUI or even a CLI-only one,
please let me know. I will write such a one and publish it on Aminet.

What about a little test? So let's go to the paragraph @{"Usage" LINK Benutzung}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Benutzung "Usage of the program"

From Workbench:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
You easily start it by double-clicking on its icon. In the window that
appears now, you open a standart ASL filerequester to enter firstly
the source file and then the destination file by clicking once on the
little gadget on the right to the two text gadgets. They are both
marked by a headline containing 'source file' resp. 'destination file'
(Info: The program can only be left if both requesters are closed!).

After the selection of the two files, you can optionally set a new va-
lue for the number of spaces that should be inserted. By default, this
value is 1.

By clicking on the button 'Insert spaces' you start the process of
inserting the spaces. When the program has finished work, it displays
the message 'Operation successfully finished' at the bottom of its
window. If an error message appears there that you don't understand
or that shows an error that you can't "repair", please tell @{"me" LINK Autor}
of that. I will then try to find and remove the bug. I will also try
to find and remove bugs that you can only find in the new ASCII text
file that the program created. In this case please send @{"me" LINK Autor} the file
with the problem and describe the it. Thanks.

Info: To choose the source and the destination at program startup, you
only have to choose at first the icon of the source file, then the one
of the destination file (both by one click with the left mouse button
and holding the shift key down), and then double-click on the icon of
the program. In the window that will pop up you can see the two (or one
if you only selected the source file) files in the two text gadgets in
the upper half of the window. Now you can alter the number of spaces to
insert (if you want to), and finally you have to click on the button
'Insert spaces' to start the "insertion" (does this word exist?).


From CLI:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
After the name of the program you can optionally name the source file,
the destination file and the number of spaces to insert. But at this
time, you have to tell the program everything that is positioned in
front of the one you need in this list. This means if you want to tell
the program at startup time which number of spaces it should use, you
have to add the two filenames, too. If you specify more than one argu-
ment, you have to use the order mentioned above.


Possible changes: @{"Future" LINK Zukunft}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Zukunft "Back to the future"

Perhaps you will be able to give the program more than one source file
at once.

Most  important: I want  to add  functions to  center the  text  to  a
user-specified number of  columns for a page,  to put it on the right,
or to format  it to something  whose name is  in German 'Blocksatz'. I
did not find it  in my dictionary, so  I will try to  show what I mean
(this   paragraph   is   formatted   as   I   mean   this   to  look).

Perhaps I will program a function that will display the text directly
in a window or somewhere else, and by which you can mark some pieces
of the text that should be reworked.

I think I should add some signs for the CLI-arguments so that you can
combine the ones you need, perhaps something like -s for the (s)ource
file and -d for the (d)estination file.

If someone thinks it would be better if there was support for Locale.
library I will include this in a new version.

Everything else must be a new idea by @{"me" LINK Autor} or hopefully
by you, the users.

@ENDNODE

